  <name>Sarracenia Purpurea</name>
  <description>_Sarracenia purpurea_, commonly known as the purple pitcher plant, northern pitcher plant, turtle socks, or side-saddle flower, is a perennial carnivorous plant in the family _Sarraceniaceae_. _Sarracenia purpurea_ attract and trap insects within their pitchers, or fused leaves, to consume nitrogen during the digestion process [A32509]. It is widely distributed across North America and has been used as a traditional medicinal herb in many aboriginal communities [A32509, A32510]. It was used as an injectable pain reliever and during the 19th century, _Sarracenia purpurea_ was used as a treatment of smallpox [A32509]. Compounds extracted from _Sarracenia purpurea_ include phenolic glycosides, flavonoid glycosides, and iridoids. _In vitro_, there is evidence of glycosides potentiating glucose uptake with potential antidiabetic properties [A32510]. Cytoprotection in an in vitro model of diabetic neuropathy has also been studied. However, the use of Sarracenia Purpurea extracts in the clinical setting are limited.</description>
